   "narrative": "Edward Day was nineteen when he died on October 25, 1777, at Troy, New York, of smallpox. He was a son of Joel and Eunice Day of Holyoke, a family that gave more to the Revolution than most: the father and five sons served, and two of the sons did not come home. His name is cut into his father's stone at Elmwood — “Edward died in his Country's Service 25th Oct 1777, Æt. 19” — but he is not buried beneath it. Sarah Rusk's record says he died at Troy and is probably buried there; where he actually lies has not been established, and Rusk herself does not claim to know. An earlier version of this entry said he was wounded in a skirmish and taken by illness within days. That was wrong. The record says smallpox. A 1929 survey lists him in the thirteenth row from the South Drive, marker 9 — at his father's stone, not at a grave of his own. If you have further information about this veteran, please contact the City of Holyoke Veterans Graves Officer at (413) 322-5630 at 310 Appleton Street, 1st Floor, Holyoke, MA 01040.",
