   "narrative": "In the summer of 1777 a British army under Burgoyne was coming down from Canada by the lakes, and every farm in this valley was sending men and food north to meet it. Joel and Eunice Day had eleven children. Joel went. Five of his sons went. Eunice ran the farm. Ticonderoga is a hundred miles north of this valley, and in 1777 the road there was an ox-cart track for most of the way. The provisions parties were farmers and their sons with wagons, moving north for days behind an army that was living hand to mouth. Nobody enlisted them. Nobody paid them. The army ate because the farms sent food, and the farms sent boys with it. Robert Day was the sixth child of Joel and Eunice Day, having gone to Fort Ticonderoga with a party carrying provisions up to the army. He was not a soldier. He was a boy carrying food to men who needed it, and he did not come back. His name is cut into his father's stone beneath his brother Edward's. Robert Day “died 27 Aug 1777, Aged 13 Years”. If you have further information about this veteran, please contact the City of Holyoke Veterans Graves Officer at (413) 322-5630 at 310 Appleton Street, 1st Floor, Holyoke, MA 01040.",
