   "narrative": "Captain Elisha Chapin, born July 16, 1707, was a provincial militia officer who commanded Fort Massachusetts — the westernmost fortification in the line of forts defending British colonial Massachusetts — from 1752 to 1754. Fort Massachusetts stood on the Hoosac River frontier of Berkshire County, the last organized defense against French and Indian forces moving south from Canada. Chapin served on the most exposed edge of the British colonial world, in a region where raids, ambushes, and sudden death were facts of daily life. On July 11, 1756, while searching for strayed cattle near Hemlock Brook at West Hoosac — the settlement that would become Williamstown — Chapin was killed by a party of Native warriors. The attack occurred as the French and Indian War was escalating across the Western Massachusetts frontier. Chapin’s marker is among the oldest military gravestones in the region. If you have further information about this veteran, please contact the City of Holyoke Veterans Graves Officer at (413) 322-5630 at 310 Appleton Street, 1st Floor, Holyoke, MA 01040.",
