   "narrative": "Captain Joseph Day went to the war as a private, in Captain Joseph Morgan's company of Colonel John Moseley's regiment — out from October 21 to November 17, 1776, twenty-eight days to reinforce the Northern Army under Lieutenant Colonel Timothy Robinson of Granville, the roll dated at West Springfield. He was out again with the same company from September 21 to October 17, 1777: one month and three days on the expedition to the northern department. The rank on his stone came later; the rolls have him a private. His brownstone at Elmwood, carved with an urn and willow, records that he died March 19, 1813, aged 67, and carries also Mrs. Azubah Day, his consort, who died December 11, 1786, aged 37 — twenty-seven years before him. A newspaper account of the Day family wonders whether he might have been the father of Eunice Day. He cannot have been: Eunice was eleven years his senior. A 1929 survey placed him in the fifteenth row from the South Drive, marker 14. He was formerly carried in this archive twice — once from the survey of his stone and once from a list of Revolutionary graves. The two are one man, and the duplicate has been removed. If you have further information about this veteran, please contact the City of Holyoke Veterans Graves Officer at (413) 322-5630 at 310 Appleton Street, 1st Floor, Holyoke, MA 01040.",
