   "extraPhotos": [],
   "narrative": "Sergeant Martin Chapin served in Captain Joseph Morgan's company of Colonel John Moseley's Hampshire County regiment. He enlisted July 21, 1776 and returned November 17 — twenty-eight days, marching under Lieutenant Colonel Timothy Robinson of Granville to reinforce the Northern Army, the roll dated at West Springfield. He went out again with the same company and regiment on September 21, 1777, discharged October 17: one month and three days, travel included, on the expedition to the northern department. He married Bathsheba Cooper in 1768. He died in April 1793, and his carved brownstone — a winged soul's head between two rosettes — is one of the most striking early stones in the burial ground. This entry formerly gave his rank as Lieutenant. Both Sarah Rusk's record of Revolutionary patriots and the stone itself say Sergeant, and the rank has been corrected here. A 1929 survey placed him in the eighteenth row from the South Drive, marker 15. If you have further information about this veteran, please contact the City of Holyoke Veterans Graves Officer at (413) 322-5630 at 310 Appleton Street, 1st Floor, Holyoke, MA 01040.",
