   "narrative": "Raymond F. Humeston served as a Private in the United States Army during World War I. He entered service on August 31, 1918, and was stationed at Camp Jackson, South Carolina — one of the great wartime training camps where hundreds of thousands of American soldiers were prepared for the front. Born in 1895, Humeston was among the young men of Holyoke who answered the call, though the armistice of November 1918 came before many of the late-summer draftees could ship overseas. He died in 1982, having lived nearly a century. He may be related to James Humeston, a Revolutionary War veteran also buried at Elmwood, though the connection is not confirmed. If you have further information about this veteran, please contact the City of Holyoke Veterans Graves Officer at (413) 322-5630 at 310 Appleton Street, 1st Floor, Holyoke, MA 01040.",
